The date of foundation is unknown.

In {{jalink|889|Q23833}} ({{jalink|Kanpyō|Q1346292}} 1), it is said to have enshrined the {{jalink|Hachiman deity|Q261637}} and been renamed “Hachimangū.”

It adjoins {{jalink|Shido-ji Temple|Q11490894}} and was destroyed by fire together with the temple in {{jalink|1479|Q6620}} ({{jalink|Bunmei (Japan)|Q1193544|Bunmei}} 11).

In {{jalink|1671|Q7610}} ({{jalink|Kanbun|Q1146228}} 11), when Shido-ji was restored by {{jalink|Takamatsu Domain|Q1036915}} lord {{jalink|Matsudaira Yorishige|Q3299364}}, the shrine was also rebuilt. At this time it was relocated to its present site (there is also a theory that it was transferred to the current location in {{jalink|1623|Q6818}} ({{jalink|Genna (Japan)|Q635245|Genna}} 9)).

Books and artifacts collected from various regions by Matsuoka Shirabe for research are preserved within the shrine as the “{{jalink|Tawa Bunko|Q11430642}} (Kōbokusha)” (Important Cultural Property).

