}}
The date of foundation is unknown.

A shrine record states: “From Yamato Province, the Ōmiwa deity was invited during the reign of {{jalink|Emperor Junna|Q329713}}, in the sixth month of the first year of Tenchō (842), to Tawa-go, Kankawa District, Sanuki Province, by the founder of the Shingon sect {{jalink|Kūkai|Q222227}} together with Fujiwara Sa-daifu Masatomi, and thus was named Tawa Daimyōjin.” The {{jalink|Ōmiwa deity|Q705542|Ōmiwa Ōkami}} is equated with Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto, matching the enshrined deity “{{jalink|Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto}}.”

The Ikoma Chronicle states, “This shrine (in Maeyama) is the Tawa Shrine of Kankawa District, Sanuki Province, listed in the Engishiki.”

The Zensan-shi records: “Tawa Shrine is located in Ōtawa, Maeyama Village. The Gokuraku-ji record says: In the eighth year of Engi (908), in the fourth month of summer, Tawa Shrine and Minono-hiko Shrine were established; this likely refers to their being listed among the government shrines. Now only foundation stones remain, and within there is a small shrine.”<ref>{{Cite web |title=Zensan-shi {{!}} Kansai University Digital Archive |url=https://www.iiif.ku-orcas.kansai-u.ac.jp/hakuen_bunko/002500426#?page=1 |website=www.iiif.ku-orcas.kansai-u.ac.jp |access-date=2024-12-19}}</ref>

; Principal deity
* {{jalink|Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto}}
; Associated deities
