The date of foundation is unknown.

In {{ill|lt=889|Q23833|WD=Q23833|1=889}} ({{ill|lt=Kanpyō|Q1346292|WD=Q1346292|1=Kanpyō (era)}} 1), it is said to have enshrined the {{ill|lt=Hachiman deity|Q261637|WD=Q261637|1=Hachiman}} and been renamed “Hachimangū.”

It adjoins {{ill|lt=Shido-ji Temple|Q11490894|WD=Q11490894|1=Shido-ji}} and was destroyed by fire together with the temple in {{ill|lt=1479|Q6620|WD=Q6620|1=1479}} ({{ill|lt=Bunmei (Japan)|Q1193544|WD=Q1193544|lt=Bunmei|1=Bunmei}} 11).

In {{ill|lt=1671|Q7610|WD=Q7610|1=1671}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 11), when Shido-ji was restored by {{ill|lt=Takamatsu Domain|Q1036915|WD=Q1036915|1=Takamatsu Domain}} lord {{ill|lt=Matsudaira Yorishige|Q3299364|WD=Q3299364|1=Matsudaira Yorishige}}, the shrine was also rebuilt. At this time it was relocated to its present site (there is also a theory that it was transferred to the current location in {{ill|lt=1623|Q6818|WD=Q6818|1=1623}} ({{ill|lt=Genna (Japan)|Q635245|WD=Q635245|lt=Genna|1=Genna}} 9)).

Books and artifacts collected from various regions by Matsuoka Shirabe for research are preserved within the shrine as the “{{ill|lt=Tawa Bunko|Q11430642|WD=Q11430642|1=Tawa Bunko}} (Kōbokusha)” (Important Cultural Property).

